# === Hyperparameters ===
batch_size = 32
epochs = 10
input_shape = (HEIGHT, WIDTH, 3)  # make sure HEIGHT and WIDTH are defined globally

# === Build the Model ===
model = Sequential([
    Conv2D(32, (3, 3), input_shape=input_shape),
    Activation('relu'),
    MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)),

    Conv2D(32, (3, 3)),
    Activation('relu'),
    MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)),

    Conv2D(64, (3, 3)),
    Activation('relu'),
    MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)),

    Flatten(),
    Dense(64),
    Activation('relu'),
    Dropout(0.5),
    Dense(1),
    Activation('sigmoid')
])

model.compile(
    loss='binary_crossentropy',
    optimizer=Adam(learning_rate=1e-4),
    metrics=['accuracy']
)

model.summary()

# === Callbacks ===
model_checkpoint = ModelCheckpoint(
    filepath="best_weights.keras",
    save_best_only=True,
    monitor='val_loss',
    mode='min',
    verbose=1,
    save_weights_only=True  
)

early_stopping = EarlyStopping(
    monitor='val_loss',
    patience=3,
    restore_best_weights=True,
    verbose=1
)

callbacks = [early_stopping, model_checkpoint]

# === Compute Class Weights from Training Data ===
class_weights = class_weight.compute_class_weight(
    class_weight='balanced',
    classes=np.unique(train_generator.classes),
    y=train_generator.classes
)
class_weights_dict = dict(enumerate(class_weights))
print(f"Class weights used: {class_weights_dict}")

# === Train the Model ===
scratch_hist = model.fit(
    train_generator,
    epochs=epochs,
    validation_data=validation_generator,
    callbacks=callbacks,
    class_weight=class_weights_dict
)

# === Save Full Model Manually ===
model.save("full_model.keras")

Instead of trying thresholds by trial-error, we can plot Precision-Recall curve and ROC curve¶

In [14]:
# Constants
TRAIN_DIR = os.path.abspath(os.path.join("..", "..", "DATA", "archive", "train"))
BATCH_SIZE = 32
WIDTH, HEIGHT = 224, 224  # Adjust as necessary

# Data generator
train_datagen = ImageDataGenerator(
    rescale=1./255,
    rotation_range=90,
    horizontal_flip=True,
    vertical_flip=True
)

train_generator = train_datagen.flow_from_directory(
    TRAIN_DIR,
    target_size=(HEIGHT, WIDTH),
    batch_size=BATCH_SIZE,
    class_mode='binary',
    shuffle=False  # Important for matching predictions with labels
)

# Make predictions
model = load_model("full_model.keras")
predictions = model.predict(train_generator, verbose=1)
predicted_probs = predictions.squeeze()  # Flatten array if necessary

# True labels
ground_truth = train_generator.classes

# Compute F1 scores across thresholds
thresholds = np.linspace(0, 1, 200)
f1_scores = [f1_score(ground_truth, predicted_probs > t) for t in thresholds]
best_idx = np.argmax(f1_scores)
best_threshold = thresholds[best_idx]
best_f1 = f1_scores[best_idx]

print(f"Best Threshold: {best_threshold:.2f} | Best F1-Score: {best_f1:.4f}")

# Plot ROC Curve
fpr, tpr, roc_thresh = roc_curve(ground_truth, predicted_probs)
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
plt.plot(fpr, tpr, label="ROC Curve")
plt.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], 'k--')
plt.xlabel("False Positive Rate")
plt.ylabel("True Positive Rate")
plt.title("ROC Curve")
plt.legend()
plt.grid(True)

# Plot Precision-Recall Curve
precision, recall, pr_thresh = precision_recall_curve(ground_truth, predicted_probs)
plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
plt.plot(pr_thresh, precision[:-1], label="Precision")
plt.plot(pr_thresh, recall[:-1], label="Recall")
plt.plot(thresholds, f1_scores, linestyle="--", color="green", label="F1-Score")

# Vertical line for best threshold
plt.axvline(x=best_threshold, color='red', linestyle='--', label=f'Best Threshold: {best_threshold:.2f}')
plt.xlabel("Threshold")
plt.ylabel("Score")
plt.title("Precision, Recall & F1 vs Threshold")
plt.legend()
plt.grid(True)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Analysis of Model Performance Based on Precision-Recall and ROC Curves¶

Our model shows promising results, indicated by the shape of both the ROC and Precision-Recall curves. The best F1-score is 0.9413, suggesting effective performance in distinguishing between the classes.

ROC Curve Analysis:¶

  • The ROC curve approaches the top-left corner, which signifies a high true positive rate and a low false positive rate, indicative of a strong classifier.

Precision, Recall, and F1-Score Analysis:¶

  • The best threshold identified from the P-R curve is at 0.22, which is substantially lower than the previously considered 0.97 in the balanced dataset scenario.
  • This lower threshold suggests that the model is confident in its predictions at a much earlier cutoff, which can be advantageous for scenarios where early detection is prioritized over the certainty of prediction.

Is 0.22 a realistic threshold?¶

  • Yes, if the model outputs probabilities that are well-calibrated and early prediction is crucial, a threshold of 0.22 ensures that predictions are made with a reasonable balance of precision and recall.
  • This threshold is particularly useful if avoiding false negatives is more critical than minimizing false positives, as it favors sensitivity over specificity.

When to Use a Lower Threshold (e.g., 0.22):¶

Scenario Use Threshold = 0.22? Reason
Want to minimize missed true cases Yes Lower threshold captures more true positives, reducing false negatives
Model gives probabilities not tightly clustered near extremes Yes Utilizes the model's confidence more evenly across the probability spectrum
You confirmed highest F1-score at 0.22 Yes Optimal performance based on empirical evidence from validation
Want to balance precision and recall Yes Ensures a pragmatic approach to handling both false positives and negatives
Want to maximize recall Yes Ideal for applications where capturing as many positives as possible is crucial
Test set has similar distribution Yes Ensures that the chosen threshold generalizes well if training and test distributions are similar

This comprehensive approach provides a clear pathway for applying the model in real-world scenarios, especially where balancing the sensitivity and specificity is key.

What is Precision in this case?¶

Precision = Of all the images the model predicted as Occupied, how many were actually Occupied?¶

High precision means few false alarms. (i.e., the model doesn’t wrongly say “occupied” when it’s actually empty.)¶

When should we try to maximize precision?¶

We want to trust the model's “occupied” prediction.¶

We want to avoid blocking spots that are actually empty.¶

What is Recall in this case?¶

Recall = Of all the actual Occupied spots, how many did the model correctly detect?¶

High recall means few misses. (i.e., the model doesn’t miss cars that are actually there.)¶

When should we try to maximize Recall?¶

We want to detect all cars, even at the cost of some false alarms.¶

We are trying to track occupancy levels accurately.'¶

We want to avoid saying “empty” when a car is there¶

In Real-World Use:¶

If our app shows drivers where to park → recall is more important (so they don’t go to an already-occupied spot).¶

If our app enforces rules (e.g., penalties for occupying unauthorized spots) → precision is more important (avoid false accusations).¶

Summary¶

Threshold Tradeoff in Parking Lot Classification¶

Threshold Tradeoff in Parking Lot Classification¶

Goal Preferred Metric Threshold Strategy
Avoid false “occupied” alerts Precision Use a moderate threshold (e.g., 0.22)
Detect all “occupied” spots Recall Use a lower threshold (e.g., 0.15)
Balance both precision and recall F1 Score Use optimal threshold from F1 (0.22)

Evalution On validation set using thresholds 0.22¶

In [15]:
# === Paths and Config ===
HEIGHT = 224
WIDTH = 224
THRESHOLD = 0.22  
valid_base_dir = os.path.abspath(os.path.join("..", "..", "DATA", "archive", "valid"))

occupied_dir = os.path.join(valid_base_dir, "occupied", "*.jpg")
empty_dir = os.path.join(valid_base_dir, "empty", "*.jpg")

# === Load All Validation Images ===
full_valid_images = glob(occupied_dir) + glob(empty_dir)
print(f"Total validation images found: {len(full_valid_images)}")

# === Load the Saved Model ===
model = load_model("full_model.keras")

# === Predict on Full Validation Set ===
full_ground_truth = []
full_pred_probs = []
full_predictions = []

for img in tqdm(full_valid_images):
    label = os.path.basename(os.path.dirname(img)).lower()
    full_ground_truth.append(1 if label == "occupied" else 0)

    image = cv2.imread(img)
    image = cv2.cvtColor(image, cv2.COLOR_BGR2RGB)
    image = cv2.resize(image, (WIDTH, HEIGHT))
    image_x = np.expand_dims(image, axis=0)
    image_x = image_x.astype(np.float32) / 255.0  # Use correct preprocessing

    prob = model.predict(image_x, verbose=0).squeeze()
    full_pred_probs.append(prob)
    full_predictions.append(1 if prob > THRESHOLD else 0)

# === Evaluation Metrics ===
print("\nClassification Report:")
print(classification_report(full_ground_truth, full_predictions, target_names=['Empty', 'Occupied'], zero_division=0))

# === Confusion Matrix ===
cm = confusion_matrix(full_ground_truth, full_predictions)
plt.figure(figsize=(6, 4))
sns.heatmap(cm, annot=True, fmt='d', cmap='Blues')
plt.title(f"Confusion Matrix (Full Validation Set @ Threshold={THRESHOLD})")
plt.xlabel("Predicted")
plt.ylabel("Actual")
plt.xticks(ticks=[0.5, 1.5], labels=['Empty', 'Occupied'])
plt.yticks(ticks=[0.5, 1.5], labels=['Empty', 'Occupied'])
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

print("\nConfusion matrix:")
print(cm)

# === Overall Accuracy ===
acc = accuracy_score(full_ground_truth, full_predictions)
print(f"Overall Accuracy: {acc:.2%}")

# === ROC-AUC Curve ===
from sklearn.metrics import roc_curve, roc_auc_score

fpr, tpr, thresholds_roc = roc_curve(full_ground_truth, full_pred_probs)
auc_score = roc_auc_score(full_ground_truth, full_pred_probs)

plt.figure(figsize=(6, 4))
plt.plot(fpr, tpr, label=f"AUC = {auc_score:.4f}", color='darkorange')
plt.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], 'k--', lw=1)
plt.xlabel("False Positive Rate")
plt.ylabel("True Positive Rate")
plt.title("ROC Curve - Validation Set")
plt.legend(loc="lower right")
plt.grid(True)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

print(f"AUC-ROC Score: {auc_score:.4f}")

# === Paths and Config ===
HEIGHT = 224
WIDTH = 224
THRESHOLD = 0.22  
test_base_dir = os.path.abspath(os.path.join("..", "..", "DATA", "archive", "test"))

occupied_dir = os.path.join(test_base_dir, "occupied", "*.jpg")
empty_dir = os.path.join(test_base_dir, "empty", "*.jpg")

# === Load All testation Images ===
full_test_images = glob(occupied_dir) + glob(empty_dir)
print(f"Total test images found: {len(full_test_images)}")

# === Load the Saved Model ===
model = load_model("full_model.keras")

# === Predict on Full testation Set ===
full_ground_truth = []
full_pred_probs = []
full_predictions = []

for img in tqdm(full_test_images):
    label = os.path.basename(os.path.dirname(img)).lower()
    full_ground_truth.append(1 if label == "occupied" else 0)

    image = cv2.imread(img)
    image = cv2.cvtColor(image, cv2.COLOR_BGR2RGB)
    image = cv2.resize(image, (WIDTH, HEIGHT))
    image_x = np.expand_dims(image, axis=0)
    image_x = image_x.astype(np.float32) / 255.0  # Use correct preprocessing

    prob = model.predict(image_x, verbose=0).squeeze()
    full_pred_probs.append(prob)
    full_predictions.append(1 if prob > THRESHOLD else 0)

# === Evaluation Metrics ===
print("\nClassification Report:")
print(classification_report(full_ground_truth, full_predictions, target_names=['Empty', 'Occupied'], zero_division=0))

# === Confusion Matrix ===
cm = confusion_matrix(full_ground_truth, full_predictions)
plt.figure(figsize=(6, 4))
sns.heatmap(cm, annot=True, fmt='d', cmap='Blues')
plt.title(f"Confusion Matrix (Full testation Set @ Threshold={THRESHOLD})")

plt.ylabel("Actual")

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

print("\nConfusion matrix:")
print(cm)

acc = accuracy_score(full_ground_truth, full_predictions)

We define a function to predict on a randomly selected image from 'test' and'valid' set with thresholds 0.22 and 0.15¶

In [24]:
def predict_random_image(set_type="valid", threshold1=0.22, threshold2=0.15):
    """
    Predict a random image from 'valid' or 'test' set using two thresholds.
    """
    assert set_type in ["valid", "test"], "set_type must be either 'valid' or 'test'"

    # === Constants ===
    HEIGHT, WIDTH = 224, 224
    BASE_DIR = os.path.abspath(os.path.join("..", "..", "DATA", "archive", set_type))
    
    # === Load model ===
    model = load_model("full_model.keras")
    
    # === Get image paths ===
    occupied_paths = glob(os.path.join(BASE_DIR, "occupied", "*.jpg"))
    empty_paths = glob(os.path.join(BASE_DIR, "empty", "*.jpg"))
    all_images = occupied_paths + empty_paths
    
    if not all_images:
        print(f"No images found in {BASE_DIR}")
        return
    
    # === Pick random image ===
    img_path = random.choice(all_images)
    true_label = os.path.basename(os.path.dirname(img_path)).lower()
    
    # === Preprocess ===
    image = cv2.imread(img_path)
    image_rgb = cv2.cvtColor(image, cv2.COLOR_BGR2RGB)
    image_resized = cv2.resize(image_rgb, (WIDTH, HEIGHT))
    image_input = np.expand_dims(image_resized, axis=0).astype(np.float32) / 255.0
    
    # === Predict ===
    prob = model.predict(image_input, verbose=0).squeeze()
    pred_1 = "occupied" if prob > threshold1 else "empty"
    pred_2 = "occupied" if prob > threshold2 else "empty"
    
    # === Display ===
    plt.imshow(image_rgb)
    plt.axis("off")
    plt.title(f"True Label: {true_label}")
    plt.show()
    
    # === Print Output ===
    print(f"Set: {set_type.upper()}")
    print(f"Image Path: {img_path}")
    print(f"Predicted Probability: {prob:.4f}")
    print(f"Prediction @ Threshold {threshold1}: {pred_1}")
    print(f"Prediction @ Threshold {threshold2}: {pred_2}")
